		<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 parent highlander-comment" id="comment-848">
				<div id="div-comment-848" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<cite class="fn">Arjan van Bentem</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://rolfje.wordpress.com/2008/09/07/a-bigger-timemachine-without-changing-history/#comment-848">
			Friday 2009-12-25 at 14:47 \14\Dec\UTC +0000</a>		</div>

		<p>Finally, Apple has documented a solution as well, for 10.6. At <a href="http://support.apple.com/kb/HT1427" rel="nofollow">http://support.apple.com/kb/HT1427</a> there&#8217;s a section &#8220;Mac OS X v10.6: How to transfer your back ups from your current hard drive to a new hard drive&#8221;, which basically is about ensuring &#8220;Ignore ownership on this volume&#8221; is not enabled, and then dragging the folder &#8220;Backups.backupd&#8221; to the new hard drive&#8230;</p>
<p>And another minor note: when connecting your backup drive after having your logic board replaced, 10.6 will even prompt you:</p>
<p>&gt; Would you like to reuse the backup [..] with this computer?<br />
&gt; The backup was created on a different computer. If you reuse<br />
&gt; this backup it can no longer be used by the original computer.</p>
<p>In the above prompt, &#8220;reuse&#8221; means &#8220;continue using, by associating it to your new computer&#8221;, rather than something like &#8220;delete to free up space for the new computer&#8221;. See <a href="http://blog.gerrior.com/wp-trackback.php?p=211" rel="nofollow">http://blog.gerrior.com/wp-trackback.php?p=211</a> for a screenshot.</p>

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/09/07/a-bigger-timemachine-without-changing-history/?replytocom=848#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-848", "848", "respond", "454")'>Reply</a>		</div>
